ons":["Day 21 after fertilisation","Day 28 after fertilisation","Day 5 after fertilisation","Day 8 after fertilisation","Day 15 after fertilisation"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eprimitive streak first appears at day 15 after fertilisation\u003C/strong\u003E, marking the beginning of gastrulation. This is a crucial developmental milestone that establishes bilateral symmetry and determines the main body axes of the embryo.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other developmental timepoints are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDay 5 after fertilisation\u003C/strong\u003E - Formation of the blastocyst\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDay 8 after fertilisation\u003C/strong\u003E - Implantation of the blastocyst into the endometrium\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDay 21 after fertilisation\u003C/strong\u003E - Beginning of neurulation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDay 28 after fertilisation\u003C/strong\u003E - Completion of neural tube closure\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe primitive streak serves as the site where epiblast cells invaginate to form mesoderm and endoderm during gastrulation. This process transforms the bilaminar embryonic disc into a trilaminar structure containing all three germ layers.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The primitive streak appears at day 15 of embryonic development and establishes bilateral symmetry.","The primitive streak determines the cranial-caudal and dorsal-ventral axes of the developing embryo.","Gastrulation begins with formation of the primitive streak, allowing migration of epiblast cells."],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57514"}